A new type of staff start-ups is now emerging to help companies find out how their staff are feeling.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure staff involvement, they enable companies to conduct express interviews, to approach certain teams and demographic groups, to offer staff with anonymity and a hotline for complaints, and in some cases to enable informers to pass the top management and to direct their direction.
“Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, and where is Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of the Glint startup from Redwood City, whose analytical programmes are used by companies to measure staff involvement.
Errett explained that she had gained a better understanding of what her staff thought and felt in three years of Glint's use.
In addition to express requests and questionnaires of certain commands, the product offers a thermal map of the company and shows in a visual form which has more complaints and which managers have low ratings, which allows it to understand why.
Companies are well aware that they need to control the situation in the workplace, otherwise they will become the next Uber, who was involved in the scandal when a former employee published a blog post describing the violent situation in which those who expressed discontent were punished.
For startups like Glint, this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for a profitable business.
The Internet portal “Let’s talk about payment”, devoted to financial technology, the global governance, regulation and compliance industry by 2020, could cost more than $118.7 billion.
The Konvercent startup from Denver, Colorado, helping companies to prevent and detect bad behaviour, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year against Uber’s reputation.
The Convergence has almost 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber appeared among the clients.
Like Glint, Konvercent allows companies to conduct individual staff opinion interviews, collect confidential real-time responses and view the thermal maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that enables staff to report misconduct.
And if they touch the top manager, the complaints go straight to the director's office.
“The public opinion court has taken over the authority of the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convergence.
If it turns out that the company is mistreated or unethical, even if the inspector does not intervene, the company may face costly consequences in the form of boycotts by clients, staff outflows and lawsuits, Quinlan reported.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants where more than 25,000 employees work in 500 establishments, has been using "Convercent" for over a year to make sure that staff are familiar with the rules and procedures, and to offer a simple way of turning to the company's principal office.
Earlier, if the staff member wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look for a phone number or an e-mail from the head office, file a formal complaint and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and awkward experience, reported James Vitrano, head of the legal office of Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track staff complaints.
Now that the company is using the Konvercent service, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states — such as discrimination, extortion and unfair pay — can be found and dealt with more quickly.
“I can get closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the situation of staff”, said Vitrano, who heads the Ruby Tuesday risk management team.
“And we protect our shareholders from court proceedings against staff.”
According to Quinland, companies began to take the ethics, values and involvement of employees more seriously in 2002, after Arthur Andersen, the accounting firm, suffered a breakdown due to ethical violations as a result of the Enron Business.
But only when social networks were widely disseminated, companies realized they could not keep their dirty underwear from viral proliferation.
“Before using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both Glint and Konvercent offer their software as a service, which is regularly paid by companies for their products.
It's a business model and an opportunity that has been approved by venture investors who have supported both startups.
In February, Konvercent received $10 million from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, resulting in a total of $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interrelated nature of companies, cultures and venture capital.
The growing scope of research shows that today ' s staff expect more jobs than before.
In competitive markets, such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects, this is just a minimum.
Staff want to feel that they are accepted and appreciated and that they are devoting their time to a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work in companies, they feel that they are heard and that the work they are doing results, they are more likely to make such a company successful,” says Nina McQueen, Vice President of Global Benefits and Satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Convergence and Glint are used.
Investors receive income when business from their portfolio goes well; companies do well when employees are loyal and involved.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase the dedication and involvement of staff, it is not surprising that they find support.
It is important to have data on the involvement of staff, according to cultural professionals in the workplace.
But the data is useless until the company's guardians take action.
In fact, if the company asks for feedback, it may give the impression that change is coming.
And if change does not take place quickly enough, or if it does not come at all, disappointment may develop, and staff members will lose interest.
“If you are going to ask for 4,000 proposals, you must be prepared to hold 4,000 interviews,” said Russell Rat, president of the management consulting firm Kotter International, who had to see companies make a mistake by relying too much on data collection.
'Why, if you do not go to the end, the staff will say, 'Did you really hear me?
You don't care?
And if you don't care, why shouldn't I care?”
According to Errett, Madison Reed, who now conducts monthly staff interviews, is able to take action on the same day as someone reporting the problem through Glint.
And after collecting feedback from staff who were unhappy with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is getting new knowledge about its staff and hopes that in the long run, this knowledge will help it to better retain staff in a sector known for its high turnover.
"If you are not trying to create a culture of transparency, you will lose people," Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose clients, you lose companies.
