A White House prop cost thousands of dollars to taxpayers
According to the weapons records provided to TIME magazine, the White House decision last month to drive a helicopter of marine infantry to the South Lawn at an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as Marine One, when the president is on board, became a central element of the event held on 17 July in the White House, where American construction programmes were demonstrated.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pens and White House senior officials have examined technological products from all 50 states.
A helicopter produced in Connecticut was launched near a yacht from the state of Man, a fire vehicle from Wisconsin, and a truck from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Squadron of Marine Infantry helicopters (HMX-1), the helicopter control unit ordered the presence of a helicopter in private order, or “FRAGO”, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of an “unusual” event.
“I just wanted you to know that you were aware of this because it is an unusually widely publicized event in the press”, said HMX-1 in an e-mail to your chief, the first Deputy Chief of Air of Marine Corps, before the event.
The letter stated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on 17 July to participate in an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and would remain there before the lawn would be released between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required to return in accordance with the restrictions on hours of service.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the operation and the security officers remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the recordings received by TIME, it was not clear whether a second crew was needed.
The Hetch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the action was contrary to that decision.
"We asked, among other things, whether this is a violation of the Hetch law, and we were told that it was not," the commander wrote.
“It seems you have nowhere to go,” answered the deputy chief.
The event “Made in America” was declared an official event by the White House and had not been covered by Hatcha law.
But even official activities have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to promote health reform, the former at the time in the Senate, and praised attempts to regulate government decisions.
The use of aircraft known as Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is unlikely to be new.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But asking for them only in the interest of photography is unusual.
Trump was already the subject of a debate in February, when a presidential plane was out in the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was bugged by complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
“The White House was thrilled by the show “Made in America”, which represented products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” said White House Vice-Secretary of the White House, Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington agglomeration and the South Lawn to train the transportation of the President of the United States to the White House with accuracy up to an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight carried out for the “Missing in America” event was estimated at the required training flights per month.
The unit helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of the “non-presidential support tasks”.
According to the White House, taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of Sikorsky reported that the company had not participated in the demonstration of the helicopter in the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not take into account the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent at the event.
However, according to the Ministry of Defence’s 2017 fiscal rate, the rate of reimbursement of the Ministry of Defence for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight.
The records of the unit indicate that the time of the aircraft in the air was 30 minutes to each side of its airfield based on the Kuantico air base in Virginia.
The White House argues that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than that rate.
“To calculate the cost for taxpayers, based on an approximate rate of reimbursement, is quite wrong,” says Walters.
“These indicative rates include personnel, services and many other irreversible costs, which are included in the annual appropriation.”
According to a study carried out by the REND Corporation in 2015, reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but do indeed take into account the fuel, service and costs specified in the contract.
At that time, former White House Spokesperson Sean Spicer spoke in defense of the use of the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to demonstrate this week the things that have been done in America,” said Spicer.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds if not thousands of people whose job depends on it.
And I think, like most Americans, we're all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment, which has been worked tirelessly by so many Americans.
It is therefore, of course, appropriate to draw this attention.”
It was not clear whether Trump was interacting with the helicopter by inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he was definitely sitting in a driver's seat in a fire vehicle.
